data.body:
In the designer-based FMod project, there is a rather bad problem with the way it handles not being able to load an FMod event. The problem arises in this code:

```
SFXFMODEventSource* SFXFMODEventSource::create( SFXFMODEvent* event )
{
   AssertFatal( event != NULL, "SFXFMODEventSource::create - got a NULL event!" );

   // Create the source.

   SFXFMODEventSource* source = new SFXFMODEventSource( event );
   if( source->mHandle )
      source->registerObject();
   else
   {
      delete source;
      source = NULL;
   }

   return source;
}
```

If `source->mHandle` is not set, it will delete the source. However this will not clear up any deletion notifications for that object as it has not been registered. This would normally not be a problem, however in `SFXSource::SFXSource( SFXTrack* track, SFXDescription* description )` we have this intriguing piece of code:

```
// Make sure we get notified when our datablocks go away
// so we can kill this source.
if( mTrack != NULL )
   deleteNotify( mTrack );
deleteNotify( mDescription ); 
```

Which adds notifications to the source object BEFORE is has been registered. This typically causes a crash as when the associated track object is being deleted it will send a notification callback to the now deleted SFXFMODEventSource.

Ideally what should happen is either of the following:
- SFXFMODEventSource::create should call clearAllNotifications before deleting source
- SFXSource::onAdd should call deleteNotify, not SFXSource::SFXSource
